I don’t think there has been another successful brand × photographer collaboration since Ganjam high jewelry and Prabuddha Dasgupta, which was so monumental and ahead of its time because it defied all kinds of logic. They set the tone for what jewelry ads and jewelry photography could look like. Prabuddha’s visual language was so distinct and so strict, and he did exactly what he wanted, always photographing on his own terms.
For Ganjam to be such a big brand at the time and still allow that kind of raw, almost nerve-wracking, anti-manicured photography is what made it so powerful. That approach has since become the crux of how so many photographers work and how India is visually represented (and how western photographers come and shoot India at large 👀☕️). He did it effortlessly, for years and years in a way that truly hasn’t been matched since.
